===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|understanden|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|understandan|understandan|to understand|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|understandanan|to stand between or in the midst of, understand|lang=en}}, equivalent to {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|under-||between|lang=ang}} + {{term|standan|standan|to stand|lang=ang}}. Akin to {{etyl|ofs|-}} {{term|understonda||to understand|lang=ofs}}, {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|understantan||to understand|lang=goh}}, {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|undirstanda||to understand|tr=Middle {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|understande|lang=da}}|lang=non}}. Compare also {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|onderstaan||to undertake, presume|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|unterstehen||to be subordinate|lang=de}}.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|understands|understanding|understood}}

# {{transitive}} To be aware of the [[meaning]] of.
#: ''I '''understand''' German.''
#: ''I received your note, but I did not '''understand''' it.''
# To [[believe]], based on information.
#: ''I '''understand''' that you have information for me.''
# To [[impute]] meaning, character etc. that is not explicitly stated.
#: ''But we cannot disappoint Grandma and Grandpa Smith, and that is what family is all about! Do you '''understand'''?!''
#: In this sense, the word is usually used in the past participle:
#: ''In the imperative mood, the word “you” is usually '''understood'''.''
# To apply values (axioms).

